&gt; &gt;DRM is about controlling how people use authority they have
&gt; &gt;already been given.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; I wont contest your definition, but my impression is that most people
&gt; dont use that definition (rightly or wrongly).  Controlling access to a
&gt; Resource (the R in URI) is about determining whether or not you are
&gt; allowed to perform an operation on that resource - are you allowed to
&gt; perform a GET/PUT/POST/DELETE.
&gt;
&gt; Which brings me to another question.  I understand that you control who
&gt; can access a URI by controlling to whom you give the URI, but how do you
&gt; control how they access the named resource.  That is, how do you control
&gt; whether or not they can POST vs GET?
&gt;
&gt; &gt;In the WSJ scenario, a subscribed user is given the authority to
&gt; &gt;read WSJ articles. The read authority implicitly carries with it
&gt; &gt;the authority to pass-on the article to others. If you can read
&gt; &gt;bits, you can copy bits. Neither capabilities nor ACLs can prevent
&gt; &gt;you from giving a WSJ article to someone who is not a WSJ
&gt; &gt;subscriber. The best you can do is make it less convenient to
&gt; &gt;share the article. That is all the WSJ ACL does. It is just a
&gt; &gt;feeble DRM measure.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; I don&#39;t even think they&#39;re attempting DRM - its not necessary.  But
&gt; that&#39;s a different discussion (one that I&#39;m not interested in having
&gt; either).
&gt;
&gt; --Chuck
